<doc id="354199" wikidata="Q720984" url="?curid=354199" title="Theodotus of Byzantium">
<text>Theodotus of Byzantium ( &quot;Theodotos&quot;; also known as Theodotus the Tanner, Theodotus the Shoemaker, Theodotus the Cobbler, and Theodotus the Fuller; flourished late 2nd century) was an Adoptionist theologian from Byzantium, one of several named Theodotus whose writings were condemned as heresy in the early church.

Theodotus held the profession of a leatherworker or fuller in Byzantium. He taught that Jesus was a non-divine man and, though later &quot;adopted&quot; by God upon baptism (that is to say, he became the Christ), was not himself God until after his resurrection.

This doctrine, sometimes called &quot;Dynamic Monarchianism&quot; or &quot;Adoptionism&quot;, was declared heretical by Pope Victor I, and Theodotus was excommunicated.

== See also ==
* Artemon
* Paul of Samosata
* Beryllus of Bostra

